Lady Mary... Ah, whoa, I'm sorry. I
didn't mean to intrude...\n< Serena>

Oh my, you're not intruding at all...
Welcome, Serena-chan.\n< Mary>

It's just that this little one isn't
full yet, so I can't leave her side...
Would you mind sitting with us for a
while?\n< Mary>

Ah... Yes... Then, I'll take you up on
your kind offer.\n< Serena>

You seem well, that's good to see. How
is your daughter doing?\n< Serena>

Yes, thanks to you, both mother and
child are very well.\n< Mary>

Well, it's tough, really tough. She
cries, she wets herself. Morning or
night, she doesn't care.\n< Mary>
But you seem to be enjoying it.\n< Serena>

That's right, it's incredibly hard...
but she's so much cuter than all of
that...\n< Mary>

When I see her latching onto my breast
and drinking milk so earnestly...\n< Mary>

I feel like I was born to meet this
child. That's why I can handle anything
with ease.\n< Mary>
For now, at least.\n< Mary>

Hmm... Lady Mary, if I may ask... does
it hurt when you breastfeed?\n< Serena>

Hurt? It's not that it hurts... Ah,
haha.\n< Mary>
Hm?\n< Serena>

That's right, Serena-chan is at that age
too. You must be confused with all the
changes in your body, right?\n< Mary>
...Yes. I am... confused.\n< Serena>

Lately, my breasts have been hurting...
I wondered if it might be an illness...\n< Serena>

Haha, don't worry. That's perfectly
normal. Serena-chan, you're getting
ready to... breastfeed a baby someday.\n< Mary>

Breastfeed... Will milk come out? Could
that pain be...!?\n< Serena>

Ah- no-no. It doesn't come out right
away. Breasts naturally start producing
milk after you have a baby.\n< Mary>
I see...\n< Serena>

That's right. Your body is starting to
prepare for that. It means you're
growing up. It means you're getting
ready to become a mother.\n< Mary>
Growing up...\n< Serena>

So don't rush it. It's surprising at
first. But it happens to everyone.\n< Mary>
...\n< Serena>

Breasts are for the baby. Right now,
your breasts are working hard for your
future baby.\n< Mary>
So take good care of them.\n< Mary>
Specifically, what should I do...?\n< Serena>

Don't touch them too much. It feels good
but you shouldn't play with them.\n< Mary>
It doesn't feel good but...\n< Serena>

Also, choosing the right underwear is
important. Something that fits snugly
around your breasts is best. Although
they can be expensive...\n< Mary>

Yes, I've tried buying some, but they
just don't seem to fit right...\n< Serena>

It feels strange at first. But you'll
get used to it soon enough.\n< Mary>

And make sure to wear something that
fits your body properly. As you grow,
your breasts will get bigger too, so
it's best to consult with an adult close
to you.\n< Mary>
Consult an adult... Hmm.\n< Serena>

And if it still hurts too much, pray to
God.\n< Mary>
To God?\n< Serena>

Yes. Thank God every day for making your
body grow properly.\n< Mary>

Because that pain is like a sign from
God saying it's okay for you to have a
baby and be happy.\n< Mary>

Then, well, it might be painful... but
you'll stop noticing it. You'll
understand it's not a bad pain.\n< Mary>
I see...\n< Serena>

That was very helpful. Very helpful
indeed. Thank you, Lady Mary.\n< Serena>
No problem, you're welcome.\n< Mary>
Well then.\n< Serena>
Oh, are you leaving already?\n< Mary>

Yes. There are things I must do. My
worries have been cleared away, and now
it's time for work.\n< Serena>
I see, well then, come visit again.\n< Mary>
Ah, I will. Until next time.\n< Serena>
Come again, Serena-chan.\n< Mary>

Serena-san... I heard. All I can do is
pray, but please come back safely...\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>Excuse me...

\n< Woman>Oh my! Welcome! Welcome, little
adventurer!
\n< Serena>Ah, yes.
\n< Serena>It's good to see you're doing well.

\n< Woman>What's wrong?

Oh, that reminds me, I haven't
introduced myself yet. In all the
commotion back then... My name is Mary.\n< Woman>

Ah, Lady Mary. Pleased to meet you. I am
Serena.\n< Serena>
Nice to meet you too, Serena-chan.\n< Woman>

\n< Mary>Jean... My husband will be home soon.
Would you like to join us for dinner as
well?

I really should decline. Tea is more
than enough...\n< Serena>

No, even tea is too much. After all,
Lady Mary, you should be...\n< Serena>
\n< Mary>What is it?

Shouldn't you be resting? You look like
you're having a hard time with such a
big belly.\n< Serena>
Really, I just came to say hello...\n< Serena>
\n< Mary>Oh, you say the same thing as Jean?

\n< Mary>But it's okay, I've been with this belly
for so long now. I'm used to it.

Used to it... and still walking around,
almost getting attacked by goblins?\n< Serena>

\n< Mary>Ahh, don't mention it. I just really
wanted some wild vegetables...

\n< Mary>My husband was really angry about it
too. He was fuming.

\n< Mary>It was the most serious scolding I've
ever received. I could feel his love...
\n< Serena>Is that so...

\n< Mary>But being able to laugh about it now is
all thanks to you, Serena-chan.

\n< Mary>You are a savior to me, my husband, and
our baby.

\n< Mary>Once again... thank you, Serena-chan.
Truly.
\n< Mary>Ahh, I'm glad I could say it.
\n< Serena>...

Hm? Your husband and... baby? Do you
have a child already? I don't see them
around...\n< Serena>
Hm-?... Ah-...\n< Mary>

Well, you see? The baby is... here.
Inside my belly.\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>...What?

...It's amazing, isn't it? All boxed up.
Should I really be telling you this?\n< Mary>
\n< Mary>But I'm going to tell you.

You see, Serena-chan, women... they grow
babies inside their bellies like this.\n< Mary>

\n< Serena>Huh?... This is the first I've heard of
it...

\n< Serena>A baby... inside the belly? How...? How
did it get in there?
\n< Mary>How... well... mmm, mmm--.

You see, a baby? When a man and a woman
love each other very much, and they
think about each other a lot...\n< Mary>

One day, the baby comes into the woman's
belly. It's a gift from God.\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>Just by thinking?
Well... it's not just that...\n< Mary>

No, this conversation might be a bit too
early for you, Serena-chan...\n< Mary>

The stamen and pistil... they come
together and... that-... eh? Will I get
in trouble with your parents for telling
you this?\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>Hmm?

Anyway, anyway, you see? A baby is the
crystal of love between a man and a
woman.\n< Mary>

At first, it's much smaller, but... a
woman takes a lot of time to slowly grow
the baby bigger.\n< Mary>

It's very hard work, but... it's
incredibly valuable. It's the most
valuable thing in this world.\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>Valuable...?

Yes--because, isn't it so? I was born
because my father and mother loved each
other.\n< Mary>

My father and mother were also born
because their parents loved each other.\n< Mary>

My father's father and my mother's
mother's mother too.\n< Mary>

For a very, very long time, since time
immemorial... feelings of 'I love you',
'I cherish you' have been passed down.\n< Mary>

Without ever being interrupted, those
feelings have been conveyed to us.\n< Mary>

And so my husband was born, and I was
born...\n< Mary>

And now we too say 'I love you', 'I
cherish you' to each other. We have
children and pass those feelings on to
them.\n< Mary>
I love you—I cherish you—.\n< Mary>

...This child will surely pass it on to
their children one day. And those
children will continue to pass it on
forever and ever.\n< Mary>

That's why the world is made entirely of
love.\n< Mary>

To say how incredibly happy we are. To
say how glad we are that you're here.\n< Mary>

People have children and raise them to
convey these feelings.\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>Me too...?
\n< Mary>Of course!

Serena-chan, me, everyone—we're all part
of a great big story of love.\n< Mary>

Lots of 'I love you's and 'I cherish
you's made Serena-chan who she is.\n< Mary>

Because otherwise, there's no way you
could have become such an adorable
Serena-chan.\n< Mary>

So Serena-chan also has a very big 'I
love you', 'I cherish you' within her.\n< Mary>

And one day for sure, you'll find
someone you want to convey those
feelings to, and have children to pass
them on to.\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>Is that so...

\n< Serena>...I had never thought about it that way
before.

I thought children were born out of
obligation.\n< Serena>

To continue the family line, to pass on
the blood. My father and mother created
me for that purpose. As their child, I
have a duty to meet those expectations.\n< Serena>

However. My family already has my older
sister. Someone many times more capable
than I am. There would be no problem if
I didn't exist.\n< Serena>

That's why I thought about how I could
fulfill my duties. As a spare for my
sister, no, rather as her support...\n< Serena>
Serena-chan.\n< Mary>
Huh?\n< Serena>

That's absolutely, absolutely,
absolutely wrong.\n< Mary>

No parent thinks of the birth of their
child, or raising their child, as an
obligation.\n< Mary>

I didn't understand it well either when
I was a daughter to my father and
mother.\n< Mary>

But now that I've become a mother to
this child, I understand. This much I
can say.\n< Mary>

A child is a parent's joy itself, love
itself. For their smile, for their
happiness, I would not spare my body, my
life, surely not even my soul.\n< Mary>
So, you see? Don't say such things...\n< Mary>

Fathers and mothers may not always be
able to convey it well, but always, at
all times, they think of their
child...nnn...!\n< Mary>
\n< Serena>Lady Mary?
Ouch...it hurts...what is this...\n< Mary>

Maybe I'm just tired from talking so
much...?\n< Mary>
